In .NET MAUI, `Application.OnStart/OnSleep/OnResume` no longer exist. Instead, lifecycle is handled at the **`Window`** level.

**Option 1: Override `Window` lifecycle methods**

Create a custom `Window` subclass:

```csharp
public class MyWindow : Window
{
    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* replaces OnStart  */ }
    protected override void OnActivated()  { /* app gained focus   */ }
    protected override void OnDeactivated(){ /* replaces OnSleep  */ }
    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* replaces OnResume */ }
    protected override void OnStopped()    { /* app no longer visible */ }
    protected override void OnDestroying() { /* app shutting down  */ }
}
```

Then in `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new MyWindow(new AppShell());
```

**Option 2: Platform-specific events via `MauiProgram.cs`**

```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));
#elif IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.OnActivated(app => { /* ... */ }));
#endif
});
```

**Mapping summary:**

| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window equivalent |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` + `OnActivated()` |
| `OnSleep()` | `OnDeactivated()` |
| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` |

Option 1 is the closest 1:1 migration path. Option 2 gives finer-grained, platform-specific control.
